Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of value added tax in the Czech Republic and Germany
Preface
The Lima Declaration adopted in 1977 stresses that sais have the power to audit all public finances.
The declaration requires that sais have the power to examine the tax collection as far as possible.
The Organisation of the European supreme audit institutions (EUROSAI) regards taxes as an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI EUROSAI Congress, which took place in 2005 in Bonn, formed the audit of public revenues by the SAIs.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of a court of Auditors is the development of a special strategy for the audit of public revenues.
This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenues with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly interlinked and interdependent, a Situation may arise in which national sais can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the sais of other states.
For example, the examination of internationally organised fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant revenue losses in many states.
Cooperation between the authorities is necessary in the fight against such offences.
Sais examining in this area must be prepared to work closely together.
The idea of an audit of VAT and system VIES originated at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of auditors.
In the course of thorough preparation, the sais involved first had to familiarise themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
Based on the analysis of the available information, we made the selection of the subject matter for the examination planning.
Achieving efficient and effective management of turnover tax is a long-standing Problem and individual states (in particular the EC member states) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of turnover tax and create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only contribute to improving the work of the financial administration, but also form the basis for a proposal for an improved System of international exchange of information.
