Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel audit
The parallel examination of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two courts of auditors.
In addition to the focus on 'exchange of information' under Council Regulation (EC) no 1798/2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) no 1925/2004, other closely related aspects were also examined, such as the registration of taxpayers, tax returns and summary declarations.
In addition, the examination also covered the legal situation of cross-border passenger transport by bus and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of Value Added Tax Administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas:
1) registration for purposes of VAT.
While in Germany the entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among other things, the essential criterion for registration is the exceeding of the turnover threshold specified in the value added tax act.
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers only receive a single tax identification number, which they also use for intra-community transactions.
In Germany, the taxable person receives a tax number only applicable to domestic transactions for VAT purposes.
If the German taxable person wishes to carry out intra-community transactions, he must issue a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID no., request.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) cross-border passenger transport by coach and bus.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport by coach and bus is exempt from VAT, but is entitled to deduction of input tax.
In Germany, the transport service, if the route passes through Germany, is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to address the Situation as referred to in Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/ EC of 28 June 2006 on the approximation of the laws of the Member States relating to cosmetic products. The commission has decided to standardise the system for the common turnover tax system (see 4.2) by 31 November 2006.
3) tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic, taxable VAT returns are only required for taxable periods during the year (month or quarter), taxable persons in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Before the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, Taxpayers in Germany have to submit VAT returns electronically.
The introduction of the obligation to submit VAT returns electronically in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech Tax Administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary Reports.
While taxpayers in the Czech Republic have to submit their summary reports to the tax offices (FÄ), German taxpayers have to submit the summary reports to the CLO2.
Accordingly, the information from the summary notifications in the Czech Republic is available to the FA immediately after their submission.
The information from the summary notifications is only available to German FÄ after the CLO has processed them.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-community transactions is needed as quickly as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the time of turnover and the updating of MIAS data.
This would allow a timely assessment of taxation in the acquirer's member state (see 4.4), but only if all EC member states introduce the same time limits.
5) international exchange of information in the field of Value Added Tax.
For incoming requests for information, the Czech CLO monitors compliance with the three-month deadline.
The German CLO does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, within the prescribed period, the German tax administration carried out a significantly lower percentage of requests for information received.
Because of these problems the BRH recommended to the German CLO, a constant Monitoring of deadlines (see 4.6).
6) risk management.
Each of the two member states shall develop its own risk management system (RMS) with appropriate strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a member state alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC member states. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the member state with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
Within the framework of the cooperation, the two sais examined selected cases of intra-community transactions carried out between Czech and German taxpayers.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed by CLO using the legal options in which there were doubts about the correct taxation or suspicions of VAT fraud.
The courts of auditors noted the following :
In some cases, the FÄ took advantage of the information obtained in the international exchange of information and redefined the VAT liability of the taxable persons concerned.
In these cases, taxable persons had either unlawfully benefited from the exemption from VAT or had not shown the acquisition of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the FÄ could not use the information obtained from the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in the two member states.
In some cases, the tax administration of another member state refused the requested information.
A number of cases have been identified in which taxable persons in their summary reports misrepresented transactions.
As a result, the data in the VIES system accordingly, so that the administrator (ABIL) had to determine in these cases (see 6).
