Comparison and evaluation
The Situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first prerequisite for registration (among others) is the exceeding of the threshold amount specified in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he may register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardized, but due to different organizational structures in the individual Länder differences may occur.
In the Czech Republic, at the time of its first registration, the taxable person receives a tax number for any tax.
In the case of his registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who can be registered for VAT purposes receives a tax number exclusively for domestic German sales.
If the German trader wishes to carry out intra-community transactions, he must specifically assign a VAT ID no. request.
Both of the NKÚ the BRH found that the German two-tier registration system may result in other member States such as the Czech Republic, which assigned a single identification number for both the national registration for VAT for intra-community transactions, significant misunderstanding.
On the other hand, the two-tier System allows retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxpayer does not register his business with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows a correct assessment of Value Added Tax for previous assessment periods, in particular a precise estimate of the value added tax liability.
As the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole EC should be harmonised.
The German parliament has recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the federal Central Office for taxes to each natural Person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
If a natural Person starts a business, the competent FA applies for a commercial tax identification number that is used as a VAT ID number. serve.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the National Registration of a taxable person and the allocation of the VAT ID no. give.
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the management of numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by coach and bus
Legal regulations in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of Section 70 of Act no 235/2004, since 1 January 2004, the provisions of Section 70 of Act no 235/2004 have been applicable. In the Czech Republic, it is exempt from VAT on the carriage of passengers between member states and between member states and third countries and is entitled to deduction of input tax.
The exemption from turnover tax applies even if the movement of persons registered as taxable persons in other member states or of foreign nationals liable to tax is carried out.
The return journey is regarded as a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than cross-border passenger transport by bus, they are not obliged to register as taxable persons in the Czech Republic.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport was exempted from VAT under the act of accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b). The above body States in the text:
'For the purpose of applying Article 28(3) (b) of Directive 77/388/EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with point 17 of Annex F to the directive, maintain the tax exemption for cross-border passenger transport either until the condition laid down in Article 28(4) of the directive is fulfilled or until the same tax exemption is applied by any of the present member states.“
The legal regulations in Germany
In accordance with article 46 of Directive 2006/112/EC of 28. November 2006, how it has been implemented in Germany by section 3b (1) of the UStG, is running a transport service where the transport is effected.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and international passenger transport.
Only the part of the transport service attributable to Germany is liable to tax in Germany.
German taxation does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (Bus)entrepreneurs.
If a taxable person who is not established moves through Germany, the part of the movement attributable to Germany shall be deemed to be a taxable movement.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must notify the competent FA of his intention to provide passenger transport services.
It shall register it for tax purposes (see 4.1.2) and shall issue a specific certificate for each bus named in the Taxable Person's declaration.
The trader must declare his taxable transport services in a German VAT return.
To the first. As of March 31, 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the FA Chemnitz-Süd.
If the transport service is provided to a trader established in Germany, the non-resident taxable person does not have to pay the VAT himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic consumers of services must pay the VAT to the tax office and the invoiced net amount to the non-resident Taxpayer. This process is referred to as 'tax liability transfer' and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC.
In addition to the declaration by a non-resident taxable person and his income tax return, the German tax administration has several means of verifying the accuracy of the tax return with regard to taxable passenger movements:
Customs Mobile control groups shall check the certificates of motor coaches approved abroad, which are used for passenger transport through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups shall submit an inspection report to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group may require the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxable person may deduct the value added tax paid in this way from the tax liability specified in his VAT return.
Where the FA has doubts as to the accuracy of a VAT return, it may order an audit to be carried out in the FA or may use the administrative assistance appropriations referred to in Council Regulation (EC) no 1798/2003 (see no 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxable person refuses to pay the value added tax, the FA may request assistance in accordance with council directive 76/308/EEC.
The BRH considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters to verify the VAT return or compliance with the tax obligation by a non-resident bus operator to be too expensive in relation to the small amount from the VAT on taxable passenger transport.
In particular, the audit of the accounts of a non-resident taxpayer entails disproportionate costs for the taxpayer himself and for the tax administration.
The latter must examine the foreign books, for which it is necessary not only to know the foreign language but also the foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an audit is likely to take more time than a resident taxpayer, although the audit is limited to passenger transport operations in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxable person must not only accept the audit rights of his national tax administration, but also those of the other member states in so far as he carries out passenger transport there.
Furthermore, for each member state in which only one passenger transport is carried out, the Taxable Person must fulfil all existing tax obligations in the different languages and on the basis of the forms issued by the tax authorities of the EC member states concerned.
Thus, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC member states and between member states and third countries is exempt from VAT under the act of accession of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the German national transport route.
Where a non-established Taxable Person provides such a transport service for the first time, he must notify the competent FA in advance.
This register the taxable person, who must declare the taxable share of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech taxpayers registered with FA Chemnitz-Süd have passenger transport as a business purpose.
