The following mechanisms to reduce risks in the field of VAT have been integrated into the Atis System: – the 'credibility of VAT returns' task to assess the risk – bearing nature of tax returns issued; – the 'selection of taxpayers to be audited' task, whereby taxpayers to be audited are selected on the basis of certain criteria;-the 'MIAS' task, which gives financial officials access to the data provided by the other EC member states.
The "MIAS" task allows, among other things, the following: – verification of the validity of the VAT ID no. of taxable persons from other member states, – confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech Taxable Person, as indicated in the CTM by all suppliers of the taxable person concerned from other member states, – establishment of a list of taxable persons who have not submitted CTM, – formal control of the information provided by taxable persons in the Czech Republic in their CTM in which VAT returns do not match the information on goods delivered to other member states with the information in the CTM, – establish a list of taxable persons in whose VAT returns do not match the information on the value of goods purchased from other member states with the information in the CTM of all their suppliers from other member states13.
As part of their role in combating tax evasion, tax officials have access to data from state authorities such as Commercial Registers, Land Registry, motor vehicle registers, trades register, etc.
