Risk management in Germany
Due to its federal structure, both the federal finance authorities (in particular the CLO) and the tax authorities of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS in the Federal Republic of Germany.
Although there are joint working groups for development, neither the CLO nor the tax administrations of the federal states have a single database.
At CLO level, unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as the 'kiss' Coordination Unit for special VAT checks and tax investigation measures) collects the fraud findings in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER was set up at the kiss. There, the tax offices can enter the names of discovered Missing Traders or value added tax fraud and also query.
The kiss coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the kiss is incorporated into the development of the RMS through their participation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal Review of the composition of signed for and on behalf. other member states which appear in the CTM of German taxpayers are carried out at the CLO.
This formal review is carried out before the CTM is transmitted to other member states in order to improve the reliability of Mia data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The verification of the validity in the ZM named USt-IdNr. done on the basis of O_MCTL identifiers transmitted by the other member states (for the procedure for correcting invalid VAT ID no. See also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO RMS relies on MIAS data transmitted by the other member states and generates various types of communications to detect alleged Missing Traders. As indications, certain characteristics are used, which usually occur in Carousel transactions.
The FES of the Länder are required to deal with these communications and have to send the outcome of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The BRH audit has confirmed that all available features must be included in order to be sufficiently close to a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the Federal Ministry of education and research has recommended that the BMF work with combinations of indications when preparing the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other indications, such as the taxpayer's payment behaviour, the economic sector or the company's ownership interests.
A second level of risk management in the financial administrations of the Federal States and focuses on the processing of VAT returns and Annual returns.
For example, the System creates a list of taxable persons who have indicated intra-community deliveries in their pre-VAT declaration or annual declaration.
This list is sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete submission of the ZM.
In addition, in this type of risk management, the acquisitions made by the taxpayer in his annual VAT return are compared with the MIA data.
The tax administrations of the federal states avoid comparing the quarterly data, as these would result in too many inconsistencies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; for example:
- Suppliers and purchasers assume different dates for the execution of intra-community turnover;
- different accounting records and tax declarations of discounts and rebates.
In addition to the comparison of the information from the VAT declarations with the VIES data, many Federal länder have certain mechanisms of risk management, based on the information provided in the VAT declarations and certain other indications (e.g., company name, age of the owner/partner, number of employees, and payment of the Taxpayer).
Bavaria has introduced a fixed rules-based risk management system that enables a Team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to program their own rules to filter out alleged tax fraudsters.
This System is used when Fä processes VAT returns.
This gives the responsible FA the information of the RMS before the value added tax is fixed.
Since this System is not learable, the risk managers must adjust the rules according to the feedback from the FA.
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania has developed an adaptive neuronal network based on the data of detected cases of backtracking.
Based on these data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The System creates a monthly list of tax cases where there are indications of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent FEC shall decide on the examination of the taxable persons concerned.
After the examination, the tax auditors must report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the examinations proposed by it.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neuronal network is used in combination with a regulation-based Fuzzy System.
Based on many data from processed VAT returns and some other indications, this Neuro-Fuzzy System (also called Datamining System) calculates how likely a taxpayer is entangled in tax fraud.
It then creates a monthly list of alleged tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the FEC shall select the taxable persons concerned for examination and report the examination results to the data centre concerned.
The introduction of these three RMS is in the States.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears to be effective.
It remains to be seen whether the expected effects will adjust during actual use.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of the RMS in the Czech and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each member state has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German Länder mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the tax authorities of the European member states on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud – in particular carousel fraud-has not proved to be a national Problem but a European Problem.
The persons involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several member states.
A member state alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC member state. If this is not the case, fraudsters will seek out the member state with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide fraud in value added tax do not necessarily affect the member state in which the Initiator is established.
Any other member state involved in the fraud may be affected.
This is why a European exchange of experience on the RMS should take place.
